    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What equipment is needed to open a restaurant in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Core equipment for any Indian restaurant: commercial cooking range (gas), tandoor (for North Indian), commercial refrigerator, commercial freezer, exhaust hood, prep sinks, work tables, and either a commercial dishwasher or manual dishwashing setup. Additional equipment depends on your menu — deep fryer for fried items, commercial oven for baked items, etc.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much does it cost to equip a restaurant kitchen in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Kitchen equipment costs for a small restaurant (20–40 covers) range from ₹5 lakh to ₹12 lakh. A medium restaurant (40–80 covers) needs ₹12–25 lakh in kitchen equipment. A large restaurant or hotel kitchen requires ₹25–50 lakh or more. These estimates cover kitchen equipment only; add 30–40% for front-of-house, furniture, and non-equipment setup costs.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What are the FSSAI requirements for restaurant kitchen equipment? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">FSSAI requires: stainless steel food-contact surfaces, adequate commercial refrigeration to maintain safe temperatures, proper handwashing facilities separate from food prep and dishwashing, commercial exhaust ventilation, pest-proof food storage, and temperature monitoring equipment. Non-compliance can result in licence cancellation.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Should I buy new or used equipment for a new restaurant? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For critical equipment (ovens, refrigerators, cooking ranges), buying new is recommended for reliability and warranty protection. For secondary equipment (work tables, shelving, non-critical smallwares), good quality used equipment can save 40–60% without significant risk. Read: <a href="/blog/used-restaurant-equipment-guide">Used Restaurant Equipment: Buying Guide India</a>.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which commercial cooking range is best for Indian restaurants? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For Indian restaurant kitchens, a heavy-duty 4-6 burner gas range with cast-iron grates is the standard. Top brands include Truehot, Venix (Indian), Vulcan, and Garland (imported). Indian brands offer good quality at lower prices and better local service. For premium kitchens, imported brands are justified by their longer lifespan and better build quality.</div>
